We recommended the Municipal Accountant to:

a.	Prepare journal entries to record the credit memo amounting to P14,180.52 of the General Fund Landbank account with account number 3322-1020-70, as shown in the bank statements and as confirmed by the bank as of December 31, 2024;










b. 	Exert earnest effort to substantiate the untraced prior year’s balances in the General Fund and Special Education Fund accounts totaling P113,628.38, as presented in Table 2.  Request supporting documents relative to unidentified items and untraced prior years’ adjustments from the bank, if necessary; 

c. 	Review the stale checks amounting to P49,858.58 and secure the addresses of the payees for notification of the return of stale check in their possession for replacement. Prepare the necessary journal entry to restore to the Cash-in-Bank balance the stale checks totaling P49,858.58; and


d. 	Ensure and examine that all of the outstanding checks reported as bank reconciling items reflected in the Bank Reconciliation Statements do not include stale checks.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to require the Municipal Accountant to:

a. 	Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify the collections to be remitted to the Bureau of Treasury and fund downloaded by the National Government to the Bureau of Fire and Protection, totaling P806,192.99 and P197,410.00, respectively, originally recorded under the “Due to NGA” account to the “Trust Liability” and                                                 “Prior Year Adjustments” Account in accordance with COA Circular 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015;




b.	Liquidate and return the fund transfer amounting to P129,500.00 to the appropriate Source Agencies as presented in Table 10;




c.	Request the write-off of the fund transfers totaling P554,437.35, as shown in Table 11, which are not reflected in the records of the Source Agency in accordance with COA Circular 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023; and 


d.	Exert utmost effort to verify the fund transfers without supporting documents and send confirmation letters once the NGA will be identified to determine if the LGU have unsettled accounts. Also, coordinate with relevant personnel and Department Heads to verify fund transfer which were not duly supported with documents.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to require the Agency Authorized Officer, Alternate Agency Authorized Officer and the Payroll Clerk to:

a. 	Reconcile with the GSIS Office the records and information of all active employees in Calendar Year 2024 such as monthly salaries to update the exact premium contributions to be deducted in the payroll and remitted for the personal share and government share as well as the outstanding loan balances to update the monthly loan amortizations to be paid by the employee;

b.	Account for the differences among the premium contributions billed by the GSIS and the amount deducted in the payroll and the amount remitted amounting to P374,535.67 and P395,285.19, respectively, as presented in Tables 13 and 14, respectively;




c.	Account for the difference between the loan amortizations billed by the GSIS, the amount deducted in the payroll and the amount remitted amounting to P345,880.94 and P419,834.99, respectively, as presented in Tables 16 and 17;




d.	Henceforth, conduct regular/periodic reconciliation of the premium amounts and loan amortizations to be withheld and remitted with the records of the GSIS Office to avoid underpaid/overpaid premium amounts and loan amortizations. The reconciliation of the GSIS accounts of the employees is not a daily activity and neither a year-round activity.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to require the:

a.	Human Resource and Management Officer to inform/provide the report to the Municipal Accountant and the Payroll Maker relative to the changes/adjustment in the salaries of the employees; 


b.	Municipal Accountant to ensure that the premiums and loan amortizations remitted tallies with the amounts withheld in the payroll. Henceforth, conduct regular/periodic reconciliation of the premium amounts to be withheld and remitted with the Human Resource and Management Officer and the Payroll Maker;




c.	Municipal Accountant/Payroll Maker to obtain regular billing for the loan amortizations from the Pag-IBIG Office; and



d.	Municipal Accountant to account for the difference between the premiums contributions and loan amortizations remitted and withheld amounting to P135,830.62 as presented in Table 21.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor immediately initiate the disposal of the unserviceable PPEs, and order the:

1.	Supply and Property Officer to submit to the Disposal Committee the following accomplished forms, as appropriate;

i.	Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) listing the properties subject for disposal;

ii.	Waster Materials Report (WMR) – covers expendable materials, supplies, and consumables, including spare parts, empty containers, and remnants from destroyed or damaged fixed assets.

2.	Disposal Committee to perform the following procedures:

i.	Inspect, appraise, and undertake valuation activities of properties as a group or individually;
ii.	If the property is to be disposed of as junk, verify parts that could be salvaged or profitably used, e.g., engine, dynamo, wheels, tires, axles, and body or chassis in the case of motor vehicles;
iii.	Set the final appraised value of the properties for disposal based on the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties;
iv.	Determine the appropriate mode of disposal and recommend the same to the applicable authorities as enumerated above for approval; and

v.	Undertake the disposal proceedings for the properties.

3.	Municipal Accountant to take up the necessary accounting entries for the derecognition of the PPEs upon disposal based on the IIRUP or WMR, and for taking up the proceeds from the sale of properties.

