This observation was communicated to Management through AOM No. 2019-009(2018) dated February 15, 2019 and discussed in an exit conference on May 6, 2019.

1. Direct the Municipal Inventory Committee to conduct regular physical inventory taking on all properties to validate all recorded balances for PPE items. To facilitate said inventory count, each department may conduct physical inventory on all properties situated within its office, to be submitted for consolidation with those prepared by the others.
2. List all Property, Plant and Equipment found on hand, classifying them into serviceable or unserviceable;
3. Maintain updated property cards per category on all property plant and equipment as recorded in the list of Property, Plant and Equipment of accounting records.
4. Reconcile property records ensuring that the balances shown in the prepared RCPPE agree with the supply records and the book balances in the accounting records, and vice versa;
5. Renew and maintain all acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE);
6. Prepare the necessary Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property and Waste Materials Report for the unserviceable properties found on hand, taking into consideration EO No. 888 March 1983, COA Memorandum No. 2005-027.
7. Direct the Municipal Assessor to produce a listing of all the properties owned by the government and reconcile them with those properties counted by the committee;
8. Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to determine the validity of the PPE account through reconciliation of the accounting records and the actual inventory;
9. Require the Municipal Accountant to:
   a. Prepare the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) for each class of property, plant and equipment listing therein the data as to its acquisition, description, custody, estimated life, rate of depreciation, disposal, and other information about the property, plant and equipment, based on the source documents of the transactions;
   b. Drop from the books of accounts the unserviceable properties after the Waste Material Report and the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property are duly approved and evaluated by the COA.
